From: Florent Revest <revestflo@gmail.com>
Subject: [PATCH] ffmemless: support FF_PERIODIC-only haptic drivers

Upstream-Status: Pending

Modern Linux FF drivers like the Cirrus cs40l26 (used on smartwatches
such as the Pixel Watch 2) advertise only FF_PERIODIC + FF_SINE +
FF_GAIN -- no FF_CONSTANT, no FF_RUMBLE. ffmemless was written before
these chips existed; it filters them out at probe, has no
FF_PERIODIC default-fallback effect, and never fires single-shot
events for them in the first place. This patch makes it work:

1. evdev selection: accept any of FF_RUMBLE / FF_CONSTANT /
   FF_PERIODIC as a sufficient indication of a usable force-feedback
   device. EVIOCSFF still fails per-effect at upload time for effects
   the device doesn't support, so this is no less safe than before.

2. Default fall-back effect: add a third branch that uses FF_PERIODIC
   with an FF_SINE waveform when neither FF_CONSTANT nor FF_RUMBLE is
   available. Combined with (1) this lets ffmemless init successfully
   on cs40l26 and similar.

3. Single-shot events: the original code only fires the FF effect when
   sound.repeat=true or haptic.duration>0 (because then sink_prepare
   bumps copy->repeat to INT32_MAX). For non-repeating events with no
   haptic.duration the default copy->repeat=0 makes ffm_play() hit the
   STOP branch and never start. On sound-less haptic-only setups
   (smartwatches with no audio) this means press / notif_normal /
   notif_strong silently no-op. Fix: treat such events as single-shot
   and fire them exactly once.

4. Per-event duration: when haptic.duration is set, also drive the
   kernel-side ff_effect.replay.length from it. Drivers like cs40l26
   BUZZGEN play for exactly replay.length ms and then stop -- writing
   EV_FF with value=INT32_MAX does NOT extend the buzz; only changing
   replay.length does. This lets events.d define per-event durations
   that the user can actually feel.

5. events.d type coercion: parse haptic.duration via a uint-then-string
   fallback. ngfd's events.d loader stores every key as a string unless
   the key is pre-registered in ngfd.ini's [keytypes] as INTEGER, so
   n_proplist_get_uint() silently returns 0 for events.d values. Fall
   back to n_proplist_get_string() + strtoul.

Signed-off-by: Florent Revest <revestflo@gmail.com>
---
 src/plugins/ffmemless/ffmemless.c |  6 ++--
 src/plugins/ffmemless/plugin.c    | 36 +++++++++++++++++++++++--
 2 files changed, 38 insertions(+), 4 deletions(-)

diff --git a/src/plugins/ffmemless/ffmemless.c b/src/plugins/ffmemless/ffmemless.c
--- a/src/plugins/ffmemless/ffmemless.c
+++ b/src/plugins/ffmemless/ffmemless.c
@@ -109,9 +109,9 @@ int ffmemless_evdev_file_search(unsigned long features[4])
 			i++;
 			continue;
 		}
-		result = test_bit(FF_RUMBLE, features);
-		result = result || test_bit(FF_CONSTANT, features);
-		result = result && test_bit(FF_PERIODIC, features);
+		result = test_bit(FF_RUMBLE, features) ||
+			 test_bit(FF_CONSTANT, features) ||
+			 test_bit(FF_PERIODIC, features);
 		if (result)
 			return fp;

diff --git a/src/plugins/ffmemless/plugin.c b/src/plugins/ffmemless/plugin.c
--- a/src/plugins/ffmemless/plugin.c
+++ b/src/plugins/ffmemless/plugin.c
@@ -269,12 +269,25 @@ static int ffm_setup_default_effect(GHashTable *effects, int dev_fd)
 		ff.type = FF_CONSTANT;
 		ff.replay.length = NGF_DEFAULT_DURATION;
 		ff.u.constant.level = NGF_DEFAULT_LEVEL;
-	} else {
+	} else if (ffmemless_has_feature(FF_RUMBLE, ffm.features)) {
 		N_DEBUG (LOG_CAT "Using rumble default effect");
 		ff.type = FF_RUMBLE;
 		ff.replay.length = NGF_DEFAULT_DURATION;
 		ff.u.rumble.strong_magnitude = NGF_DEFAULT_RMAGNITUDE;
 		ff.u.rumble.weak_magnitude = NGF_DEFAULT_RMAGNITUDE;
+	} else {
+		N_DEBUG (LOG_CAT "Using periodic sine default effect");
+		ff.type = FF_PERIODIC;
+		ff.replay.length = NGF_DEFAULT_DURATION;
+		ff.u.periodic.waveform = FF_SINE;
+		ff.u.periodic.period = 50;
+		ff.u.periodic.magnitude = NGF_DEFAULT_RMAGNITUDE;
+		ff.u.periodic.offset = 0;
+		ff.u.periodic.phase = 0;
+		ff.u.periodic.envelope.attack_length = 0;
+		ff.u.periodic.envelope.attack_level = 0;
+		ff.u.periodic.envelope.fade_length = 0;
+		ff.u.periodic.envelope.fade_level = 0;
 	}
 	if (ffm.cache_effects) {
 		memcpy(&data->cached_effect, &ff, sizeof(ff));
@@ -719,6 +732,15 @@

 	repeat = n_proplist_get_bool (props, FFM_SOUND_REPEAT_KEY);
 	playback_time = n_proplist_get_uint (props, FFM_HAPTIC_DURATION_KEY);
+	if (!playback_time) {
+		/* Events.d stores unregistered keys as strings, so
+		 * n_proplist_get_uint() returns 0 for haptic.duration
+		 * read from events.d -- fall back to string parsing. */
+		const char *s = n_proplist_get_string (props,
+				FFM_HAPTIC_DURATION_KEY);
+		if (s)
+			playback_time = (guint) strtoul (s, NULL, 10);
+	}
 	if (repeat || playback_time) {
 		/*
 		 * If duration was not defined, it's zero and we don't report playback
@@ -729,8 +751,20 @@
 		if (!copy->playback_time && playback_time) {
 			copy->playback_time = playback_time;
 		};
+	} else {
+		/* No sound.repeat AND no haptic.duration: single-shot
+		 * haptic. Fire it once -- without this branch copy->repeat
+		 * stays 0 and ffm_play() takes the STOP path. */
+		copy->repeat = 1;
 	}

+	/* Drive the kernel-side effect length too, not just the cleanup
+	 * timer. cs40l26 (and other timed_output / BUZZGEN style drivers)
+	 * play replay.length ms and stop; looping the EV_FF write does
+	 * not extend a buzz. */
+	if (playback_time && playback_time <= G_MAXUINT16)
+		copy->cached_effect.replay.length = playback_time;
+
 	N_DEBUG (LOG_CAT "prep effect %s, repeat %d times, duration of %d ms",
 			key, copy->repeat, copy->playback_time);
